  "text": "Mitochondrial dysfunction was suggested as a unifying pathophysiological explanation for PD and other neurodegenerative disorders. Mitochondria are the most efficient producers of adenosine triphosphate (ATP) and play an important role in calcium homeostasis and in the initiation of apoptosis. In the case of severe oxidative phosphorylation defects, the ability of mitochondria to handle calcium is impaired [CITATION_1] . Moreover, mitochondria are a major source of reactive oxygen species (ROS), including manganese superoxide dismutase (Mn-SOD, SOD2), and promote defense mechanisms against ROS-mediated damage. Hence, mitochondrial and oxidative stress are implicated in a number of neurodegeneration and aging-related disorders. Genes associated with autosomal recessive PD are reported to be involved in the control of the mitochondrial function. Phosphatase/tensin homolog deleted on chromosome 10-(PTEN-) induced putative kinase 1 (PINK1) and Parkin genes controls the elimination of impaired mitochondria via autophagy (mitophagy) [CITATION_2] .",
